#### Issue details

When using HttpRequest to send a DELETE with JSON content, it does not work properly and the JSON is ignored
#### Reproduction steps/code

Try the following code with a proper REST service supporting DELETE command:

``` java
         HttpRequest httpGet = new HttpRequest(HttpMethods.DELETE);
         httpGet.setHeader("Content-Type", "application/json");
         httpGet.setHeader("Accept", "application/json");
         httpGet.setUrl("https://myservice.com/main/v1/user/me/achievement");
         httpGet.setContent("{\"achievements\":[{\"achievement\":\"MY_ACHIEVEMENT\"}]}");

         Gdx.net.sendHttpRequest (httpGet, new HttpResponseListener() {

            @Override
            public void handleHttpResponse(HttpResponse httpResponse) {
                try
                {
                    String result = httpResponse.getResultAsString();
                    Json json = new Json();
                    Map<String, Object> test = json.fromJson(parameters.getClass(), result);
                    if (httpResponse.getStatus().getStatusCode()!=HttpStatus.SC_NO_CONTENT)
                    {
                        if (listener!=null)
                            listener.removeAchievementFailed("Status not ok: " + result);
                        return;
                    }
                    if (listener!=null)
                        listener.removeAchievementSucceeded(achievement);
                }
                catch(RuntimeException e)
                {
                    if (listener!=null)
                        listener.removeAchievementFailed("Error parsing httpResponse");
                }
            }

            @Override
            public void failed(Throwable t) {
                if (listener!=null)
                    listener.removeAchievementFailed("Connection failed");

            }

            @Override
            public void cancelled() {
                if (listener!=null)
                    listener.removeAchievementFailed("Connection cancelled");

            }
        });         
```

After analysis the problem come from the com.badlogic.gdx.net.NetJavaImpl class in the method sendHttpRequest.
If you look at the code, the GET, POST and PUT method are taking into account and not the DELETE.
Especially with the doingOutput which should be true for DELETE.

The sending of httpRequest.getContent() is conditionned by this flag so it is not sent for a DELETE.
